content: Fantastic game, I play it once a year
Great game, have played it many times before on desktop but this was my first time on mobile. 100% worth the $1.99
Hoping for a more detailed ending, but everything else was fun
Barebones RPG. Excellently balanced, great story with amazing progression. If you're a fan of classics this is a must play.

Found this game web version when searching for unusual RPGs. Played it until finish. But was curios about the android one, so downloaded one for free and played once more until finish. I Respect the makers that's why I bought this game. Nice one, this inspires me. (To be honest the web version is a lot harder. In this android version I don't even need any rifle or carbine or grenade to finish, having four hands to wield four melee weapon is great afterall, oops, hope that wasn't a spoiler) :D
Easily the bast mobile game I've ever played.
Better than the web version. I played the web version years ago and I expected the app to be watered down. It was not.
Compelling!
Incredible game. The controls could be better though

I dont want to spoil anything, so I will just say this. This game honestly made me rethink my life and wonder if I am like the main character(just not on a big scale). This game made me feel empowered, but guilty at the same time. I almost deleted the game because I didn't want to go through this, but I decided not to. If you want to play this game, be ready for a shocker.
tbh, I'm not much into text based rpg games until i discovered this treasure. probably the best game i had ever play. thank you developer.
A very great game. I only wish the items were organized more legally in the supply tab.
The online version is way better
Excellent. Has depth.

Absolutely amazing game. The story that was crafted is captivating and gave as many questions as it did answers. If you're reading this and are confused as to what story I mean, just stick with the game for a little bit. It start out slow and simple but quickly becomes something much more, and even makes you think about what your morals are. I guarantee that this game is worth every cent.
Pretty good game
Elegant gameplay. The sense of wonder is so well done. The simplicity is beautiful.
Simplistic yet intriguing
Very unique game. My favorite mobile game by far
It's unlike any other game. It's a slow burn mystery, but completely addictive. Just play it.
This was a great game for a little bit of money. It takes a bit to get it going, but it's very neat. Recommended for people like me who are picky about mobile games.

what an awesome little game that paces the discovery based learning how and what to do. engaging backstory that's a bit mysterious but adds to the reason to keep playing. love that you can jump in and out of play and it's not too brutal is you mess up

One of the best games I've ever played, period. Don't need graphics to completely enjoy this game. Very well put together. I'm an old fan of mud games from the 90's so I was looking for a new text game to play. I highly recommend this one. Thank you guys!

Really good game, but feels a bit short for 2 dollars. I was hoping there would be a few more mechanics or things to explore. Since it is a linear storyline, once the game ends you start over from scratch. Besides the length it is a solid game though.

It's so simplistic, and would seem boring but it isn't. It's a game that is relaxing, there is no sound it doesn't get your heart pumping, but pulls you in with it's mysteries. You want to know more, want to figure out the story of this simplistic world and it keeps you questioning. It's ambiguous and there are no straight answers. But it keeps you asking. I don't often play games more than once, but with this one, i keep coming back to play it again. It is worth the money.
Super fun!! Want more!!
Fun game, good story

Got this on sale and played it years ago and enjoyed it. Read an article that mentioned it and decided to give it another run recently. It's still enjoyable, although it's not the kind of game you're going to want to return to more than once every few years. Despite the looping storyline its linear nature means that it's really only fun for two playthroughs, one evil and one good. If you haven't played it, though, it's highly recommended, as it's different than anything else on mobile.
A good distraction for a dark room
Great Game!
Fantastic story, even if it's not told outright. To be so very simple, it is a truly amazing world in which to find yourself!
Loved this game! Both the app and the PC version are great.
The original browser idle game that we all know and love. Still exactly the same as in 2012 and better off for it. Never change Amir.
I last played a few years ago, it just seems depressing now with how the village turns... yeah. Not a bad game, just not good for me mentally this year.

I bought this game for the low buy in and the positive reviews. After playing it for hours I don't understand the appeal. Everything takes place through text and you just watch bars fill as resources are collected. You build buildings and items but there is no indication of the effects any of them really have. This must be a very niche game and don't recommend it for most people.
very fun minimalist rpg experience. very repayable as well.
A wonderful game! I played the browser version and remember it fondly. I'm glad I got this one as well.

An interesting idle game. Don't be fooled by the sparse graphics. It's got thrilling fights and mysterious characters. Relatively short but with multiple ways to play that change the experience and interactions, plus a new map each playthrough.
The Room is dimly lit
Fun game but there is a bug where the supplies screen goes blank part way through playing
A very very short game, took me less than 4 hours to finish it, not sure if its worth the money

content: Has always been a great game, glad it's on mobile now.
I liked it. It was good.
meh
A charming little game, an interesting and mysterious world, and simple, fun text based gameplay
Magical. Takes patience. Play it through. Ponder.
Fun
Interesting experience. Slows down in the mid-game, makes you grind a pretty absurd amount of material, but I had fun. Cool story, especially once you realize the big picture.
Great game. Great story. Very simple yet deep and engaging.

What a ripper! Bought this game on iOs years ago then bought it again on Google play cos it kicks ass. Best text based rpg out there hands down. Love the economy you build and the exploring features. Very well made game 5 stars
Excellent game. Everything i was looking for in a word based game.

I first played this game on my iPhone back in 2015. Now, years later, I decide to get the game again only to find it's not quite the same (not counting minor graphical differences). For example, on the map, you can only encounter three types of foes, from a snarling beast to a feral terror. In the original, there were nine foes you could encounter, including a lizard, a scavenger, a sniper, and a soldier. I'm not sure why these were cut, but it's really lame. Also, the asteroids look different.
I've played through several times and decided to download it again. It's super entertaining and has a lot of replayability.

So nostalgic. I played this game about 7 years ago on my ipod. If you can't drift to sleep at night, this game will tire you out and your imagination. It looks so simple but it's surprisingly really fun. Geeettt iitttttt
Verry fun artistic experience with mystery and cool twists.
Not as good as the web version
An incredible experience in interactive story telling. Simple and engaging enough to keep you hooked until the end
Really kind of profound. Great game.

Enjoyable and surprisingly emotional text game. Fun discovering what you can do as each stage emerges. I would allow older children to play and also would work for vision impaired players with a screen reader.

Don't stop playing this game. This text based adventure was recommended to me by my roommate, and I couldn't have enjoyed it more. It made me feel terrible, and inquisitive. Just enough story to snag me, but not too much to overwhelm it's simplicity. I'm so glad I played it through to the end.
Remind me of the simple rpg games I used to play on floppy disk.

This is one of the few games that i give a rating to when it asked me to. And yes, five stars. Unlike the bland, boring, copypasta that is mobile games, a dark room is genuinely good. It does not: .Shove ads down your through whenever you do stuff .Have an "energy" system where you must wait for you energy to refill before playing again .Constantly put a message in your face asking you to rate it Its everything you want. Fun, creative, and a decent story. Highly reccomend over other mobile games
Not optimized for my note 9. Be warned the home button, back button and multitask are all permanently locked on screen while using the app.
Very emotional for a text-based adventure game, about 3 hours of entertaining gameplay that's hard to step away from and leaves you wanting more
Surprisingly deep text art RPG. If you like retro games this one might be interesting for you.
Excellent game, I give it a new play-through every couple years and I was pleased this time around to find the secret "no-huts" ending!

I know it feels unfamiliar at the start but if you just keep going you'll find this is an excellent indie game that even has a intriguing plot. When your stuff gets stolen you still get something for it so you are never really losing progress. It's good. Give it a chance.

I played it on desktop and when I came across it in the app store I knew I had to have it. Simple in gameplay, the game occasionally leaves you with little snippets of backstory to ruminate on until the next text event. Currently trying to finish the game without any huts - it's harder than I thought! My only regret is that on desktop you could tab out and the game would keep running in the background while you can't do that on mobile as far as I've seen.
An absolutely unique game and experience that I couldn't even begin to explain! Seriously addictive and deep! 10/10!
An incredible piece of art
Some bugs but nothing that broke the game for me. I would really really like a lights out mode like the web version has. Just completed. Very good.
Great game
Such a good experience!

Not a fan at all. Wish I wouldn't have paid 2 dollars for this. The menus are annoying to navigate and the whole idea of your villagers becoming slaves is awful. I did not enjoy being slapped in the face with this whole you're horrible thing. The exchange rate also seems ridiculous compared to the browser version. I can tell there was a lot of hard work put into it and that's why I left 3 stars.
Love it.
Still amazing even though it's been years since I played

This is an absolutely incredible game, i have played through it a couple times, but nothing can beat that first time experiencing it. I understand that text based adventures are not for everybody, but i would definitely recommend this to anyone looking for an extraordinary experience. I posted this in 2015 on the wrong app 🙄. I decided to download and replay for the countless time and saw my error. Amir, I love this game, very well thought out. Thank you.

Few bugs here and there, and economy management suffered a bit compared to browser version. But the new ending/commentary is a welcome feature and well worth price of entry if you liked the browser version. Noticed bugs: Commentary stops after leaving screen Perks showing my resources Perks showing all available perks despite not having them unlocked Damages sometimes going haywire
Classic
Sweet game!
Great game, well worth the small price
Lovely
one of the few good mobile games
An excellent clicker game with an air of mystery about it.

This is truly a masterpiece for those looking to build up their own worlds with only the bare minimum of data presented to them....loved it and really look forward to a sequel if there ever will be one😁😁
Between thieves in the supplies and feral terrors killing you every time you journey out , this game should be put in a dark room and forgotten.
Amazing
This game will suprise you.. Fantastic game!

Layers upon layers. Your hand isn't held, and you play in your own way. A challenging text based game that manages to suck you in to this world. You won't notice the absence of 3D graphics, animations or sprites. Masterpiece.

Felt nostalgic for the web version, and looked on the app store. I found this paid version and was disappointed that it wasn't free, but I paid up since I knew I'd enjoy it. Turns out, I hadn't even experienced the most important parts of the web version, and the mobile version has even more! This was definitely worth the purchase and inspires me to share and make more myself. Get this game, and if you are on the fence, play the free, original, web version first to let the fire warm your heart.
One of the few mobile games I always come back to and have actually enjoyed. No annoyances, just pure gameplay. Really fun text based adventure game with great mechanics.

Can't deal with the inability to grow without slaves. Just... Can't do it. The minute I saw huts meant you had to have slaves, I couldn't play anymore. Which sucks, the concept is awesome. Game play and concept is 5, but... The slaves kills those 2 points.

A classic game that I remember playing, and to this day I still thoroughly enjoy it. Definitely worth downloading! The story itself is very ominous, and whichever ending your try to go for is always worth it in the end.
Addictive

This is the 2nd time ive tried this game. The first time i got stuck and uninstalled it bc of lack of memory on my phone. This game is really fun and creative. A friend of mine recommended it to me. I love the ascii map. I like the mystery of the story too.
Intriguing plot, good development, and a well-done adventure system.
Best game ever that I played on my phone
If you haven't played this, you should. This is a fantastic example of how a simple concept can be so incredibly grasping and immersive.

I like this game, but its much more fun in a browser where it can be in a different tab and your resources still grow VS the app where it needs to be open constantly to work. It's like an idling game but you need it open all the time- and the choices /plot aren't worth the phone battery. Play it in browser, don't waste 2 bucks like I did when browser is better for free.

This game was fanominal being a person whose played alot of video games and even is a decent beta tester for more. I haven't had as much fun playing a texted based game before in my life. I bought the game back in 2013 as 13 year old me had a short attention span, a iphone 4, and pretty much bought it and dropped it. As this happens with alot of 13 year olds, I'm 20 years old now, in the military, and played it while I am in quarantine in germany. 5/5 the locket glows, must find her <3
Tedious gameplay, boring story. Grindy and unrewarding.

Very cute game, but there still are various bugs which impact the play. Resources are not shown in supplies. The perks you've gotten are not shown (it showed all available perks for me always) and in my second playthrough it even showed resources on the perk page. The second playthrough my map gets reset every time I restart the game.

Simple but amazing game :) ...don't be scared of the simple beginning and def stick with it! The cherry on top was the audio clips at the end. Loved the personal connection and also just insights to creating it. Please come out with a sequel!

I played this game for the first time on my brother's iPad about 7 years ago or so, and I loved it. But I was only 10, so I didn't really understand a lot of the underlying themes, but now that I do, it's made this game so much better. It will always be one of the best games I've ever played.

Just reached the end. The story was absolutely amazing, even if it was vague; in fact, the vagueness probably made it even better. I absolutely reccommend playing this game, even if it starts out slow at the beginning!

Enjoyed this game immensely - this version has more story than the free version available online. Well worth the paltry cost. Beating it unlocks 'secrets' (audio commentary from creators) and a clue on how to get a different ending.
Depressing, simple, and fairly fast. Love it.

Honestly one of the three greatest games I have ever played. If you have fought your way through, then you know how worthwhile it is. May the fire burn brightly for you, friend. Seriously, stick it out through the first part. It's not what it seems. Not at all.
A splendid game for 2 dollars.
It's a great game. Take some time to it, it's an incremental game after all. I was surprised with the story.
This is one of the defining games of its genre. It's worth every penny.
Really interesting game. Playing it felt like an experience

I live for the subtle, often single-word-based storytelling and world-building methods ADR employs because they're not overbearing. The minimalist graphical style allows you to formulate your own visuals, while the story evolves those mental images over time with . I still vastly prefer to web version, as the app feels a little clunky, but the expanded universe is well worth the time taken to replay my favorite browser game over again with different flavors added to the mix.
Still a great game, not quite as smooth as the browser version, but also less tedious.

The game is great I have been playing the game for week now. Love the game hope u make more updates in the future. Tips for gamers: adventure in the dusty path bring a lot of cured meat and u will be able to beat the game faster.

There are some bugs but this is by far the best mobile game experience I have ever had. My completion time is 206 minutes and I wish there was more because this game is amazing. When the civilians turned into slaves I had a feeling of regret and worry. Then the builder began having the same emotions as I had I felt as if I was getting corrupt, greedy, and evil. I started to think maybe I'm bad maybe these people are just trying to survive and I am attacking them. This was truly a journey.
A wonderful little game, kept me curiously occupied from beginning to the end
Really fun game!

I think it was a fun game but the problem is that when people come to stay and ask for lodgings you say yes if you don't have the material. but you could get the material why he is getting his home for the night "homey". I don't think that you should make your villagers slaves because it is mean and maybe you could have a different ending depending on wich path you choose. e.g. you could be mean so the villagers leave you or you could be nice so the villagers work extra hard. It was a good game.
Please just give it the chance.
Fast. Phenomenal. Perfect.
Strange but fun
Lil different from the computer version but that's a good thing!

What an amazing experience! Didn't know what I was getting in to, thought it was going to be your average idle game, but this is far more than that. It's an RPG like no other. Don't bother with the clones and support these devs!

Played this to completion at least 15 times, it gets harder to beat it every time... Text based games rule! NB after years of using this app, it started giving a crash like result while exploring. This made the game unpleasant and for now, I've uninstalled it. Deducted 1 star for no response to my feedback as a beta tester
Very engaging and insightful, wish controls were a bit easier like being able to tap the area you wanna go to

fun experience, but there is a bug where the game would reset while I'm exploring. my progress is saved, but bits and pieces of explored territory gets erased so I have to travel there to reveal it again. for example, the iron main I found is still there and owned by me, but the mine and the path to it have disappeared until I find it again
Such a nice little game but we need the prequel on Android!!

Please fix this issue. The perks just shows Ive got all of it while it's not. Ive been buying maps from a scout, the revealed area disappear everytime I reentered the game. Doesnt shows how much the resultant rate of production for automated salvaged materials(WHICH PC HAVE, AND PC VERSION IS FREE). Recently, I was about to leave the emptied deserted town. Suddenly, the screen just switched to the dusty path menu.
Good game, worth the $2
I love it even more than when I found the web browser version way back when. Such a fun and interesting storyline.
good
Plan rides fly by
This game is really inovative, subverts your expectations, and has a great atmosphere. I highly recommend it- easily worth the price.
Outstanding. Possibly the best game I've ever played in my phone.
A friend recommended this one to me. It's a good time killer. Fun little indie game.
Thoroughly enjoyed the game. Thank you
Honestly I've never played a game like this that has gripped me so much I usually have a short attention span but I couldnt put this down
love this game. a work of art
Started playing the PC version so got the mobile version. But this version is quite bad when it comes to alignment and placing of text and buttons. Kind of unplayable because of it.
Interesting game really makes you wonder what's coming next
I've played this game several times and it always surprises me. Delightful game that challenges the normal video gamer's way of thinking.
Brilliant
I loved it! It is weird and confusing at first, until it becomes weird, confusing and... amazing! Just play it.
Very well spent couple of hours
Very addictive game, this game is totally yet driven and yet it manages to make me think about what will happen next.
One star because this format sucks compared to the computer browser version
Though there's a few questions left unanswered , the whole experience is well worth the asking price!

Amazingly great game, a bit short and a tiny oversight(when you build a wagon/convo you don't gather more wood, which doesn't make sense) but other than that nitpick, it's fantastic and well worth the money.
Fun and intriguing. Honestly, I just wish that it were longer. There are times when the UI is a little clunky though.
Brilliant little game! A rewarding, minimalistic story with a fascinating twist just when you think you've got it all figured out.
Brilliant.
Meh. I found the story too vague, and didn't realize the twist until after I played it, which was too late.
This games narrative is breathtaking. I had a lot of fun playing it and having these experiences. Playing it the second time with a challenge. No huts.
Immersive
I could not put this game down!
Absolutely stunning piece of work.
A unique experience

One of the greatest games I've ever played. It does so much more than I could've possibly imagined. It's one of those "everything isn't what it seems" kind of games where the conclusion leaves you satisifed but wondering if you caught everything (which unless you were actively using a strategy guide then no, you won't in the first run). Highly recommend this game, even if you've never played a Text Based game (this was my first). I would love to play anything the developers come out with next.
Been playing this game on and off for years, always a good time!
I'm not going to give soilers, but the web version is better.
Simple games with lots of fun. No pay to win. Great!
Amazing game. It was very confusing at first but by the end i was wishing there was more after the end.👍👍👍
Excellent
A really well paced game with a compellingly abstract narrative. I only wish there was more to explore and uncover.
Horrific
The setup is clunky and just doesnt feel good. The desktop version is much better.
Yeet
So much fun!!!
Great
Heart Sinking Good
Bugs here and there and not enough content. However, what content there is is extremely good. Time well spent in my opinion.
Excellent game, big surprise. One of the most original and interesting games I've played on mobile.
This game is outstanding. Worth paying for.
The browser version is better because it doesn't try so hard. The weird plot elements in this version don't improve anything.
Phenomenal atmosphere, exploration and story. Everyone should experience this game
Excellent single player incremental game with a mix of generes.
One of the best indie games I know
Worth pushing through the simple and ambigious start. If you enjoyed this, check out Paperclip Maximizer online.

I played this game on iOS years ago but didnt finish it. Purchased it again on Android and finally finished it this time. The game itself is brilliant. The story and the experience is unique and I thoroughly enjoy the resource cmanagement. However, I had some near game-breaking bugs. 4/5 times one of two bugs would occur: supplies missing from the supplies list and appearing in the embark screen, making management near impossible, or all perks being listed on perks screen. Otherwise, great game.
Delightfully simple idea that does a good job containing all the storytelling elements that made all the rogue likes a hit.

Played the browser version multiple times and loved it, was concerned about paying money for the same experience. The added components give another layer of immersion, well worth the money. Great game.
Love it. I thought the story was over, and then it kept going.

The UI is an issue. Sometimes there is a "the workers are tired and happy" text that overlays OVER the buttons that let you play. You can't close it, you have to wait. Supplies are on a separate screen. Just poor UI work that makes it hard to know what you have and how much things are.
I love this game! Very fun, had to buy it for mobile.
Super interesting way to play an idle game, fun twists and well made.

I've played through the PC browser version many times and love this simple yet incredible experience and that experience is even deeper in this mobile app version. I absolutely love this game and highly recommend it in both forms to anyone who can appreciate indie text based and resource management games but most definately the app version for the added depth to story and gameplay.
The game is pretty fun, and a good time killer, but it just takes way too long to build up the resources to get buildings.
Keep the fire going.
Hmmm great ideea for a game but a bit boring, want a refund
A wonderful expansion on one of my favorite browser games. Definitely worth the purchase.
Amazing!!!
Sadly, the UI is better on the computer. Its a great title but the app ruins the experience.
One of the best text adventures in recent years
Simple, but extremely creative and entertaining! I had a lot of fun building up my village, and it was really mysterious throughout.
Excellent! Avoid all spoilers.
One of the most beautifully crafted games I have ever played in a long time with a stunning story behind it all the price is amazing for the quality of game. I would live for a part two of this game
Pales in comparison the web version. The UI obfuscates and hides so much of what the user needs to do and know.

I tried this game a few years back on the web version. I really liked it but could never get fa, for whatever reason. The added lore was very interesting and had me thinking of how other similar games are. Definitely worth the $2
Speechless

Superb. A simplistic, yet fantastic experience. At a glance, it might looks just like another idle game without all of the usual bells & whistles, but it's much more than that. Give it a try if you've never played this or the original web version. Kudos to the developers.

Absolutely brilliant!!! I purchased this game on IOS years ago looking for text based games dreaming for more. I have gifted it to a couple of other as well who have enjoyed. The only thing I ask is you port 'The Ensign' into android
Overall pretty decent, was enjoyable and simplistic, but not rounded through as much as it could have been. 3.5/5 or so.
Chills. This game is good.
Honestly a great game, love the idea, wish there were a bit more description in some of the creatures

Hyper minimalist resource gathering and exploration game, that also manages to tell a surprisingly good story with very few words. I'm surprised at how invested I became after just a few sentences of descriptions. A simple yet compelling game.
Great game, wish the other games would come to android.
Stick with it... it's worth it...
it's ok I guess
Excellent game - it took me about 6.5 hours to beat, but I'm sure you can do it faster. The game is addicting - with everything you do you learn just a little bit more about the world.

"He asks about her..." Just spent the evening binge playing from start to finish. I originally started a playthrough in-browser almost two years ago and never quite finished; recently found it as a mobile app and decided to give it another go. It's now 230am and I regret nothing. Interactions with the builder lended a surprisingly dark complexity that had me hooked all the way to the end.
A great game with a thought provoking, slowly unfolding story.
A beautiful yet simple story, and engaging yet simply gameply. Not much else to say other than go play it yourself.
Great game. Its very addictive. Make more!
I love how it wraps up unexplained details that were in the PC version, and the added story line and friedrich nietzsche refrences
just play it. it starts off and seems blah but it gets really good
What an excellent experience. Brilliant game.
Excellent incremental game. Decent play time, engaging all the way through, and after you complete the game once, you can really see how much the devs care about what they do.
Fun non run of the mill game. That even has a cool twist story. Well worth the buy

Not to be noted for graphics, but this game is amazing. Random scenarios pop up and ask you: do you want to take the chance to lose your people, or gain some materials? This is a very well made game not made to be an addicting one but it is addicting soley since it is so good. Definitely worth the one dollar, and looking at it: more, if you'd ask me.
Simple, intriguing, fun
Always get chills at the end. great game.
Amazing game with a compelling storyline. Well worth the $2. If you think it starts too slow, just give it a chance. it will blow you away.
To short though

I bought this game out of a whim, thinking to myself "eh, why the hell not? It doesn't cost that much". What I got was something extremely unique and I feel is worth so much more! This is just a survival game, but putting it like that is leaving out so much the game has to offer. The story is great, although the UI and the way you navigate throughout the world looks disconcerting, don't let that stop you from getting into the great narrative that is "A Dark Room".
A classic. I will never forget this game or how it informed my thoughts on narrative.
Absolutely unique and phenomenal.
Absolutely a great game.
It was a fantastic and interesting game to play with lots of cool secrets and is isn't too easy to complete but not to hard. Thank you for creating such an awesome game

A very unique experience. Going into it I was thinking it was gonna be like the old text adventure games which is true to an extent, yet it was so unique in my eyes I couldn't compare it to anything. A Dark Room is a true piece of art that everyone should try out.
A powerful, subtle, simple and complex game that makes you think. I keep coming back to it and would love to see more of its kind.
An amazing game that you can only experience for the first time once. Worth every penny. A unique experience.

A must try unique in its own way ... Although things could be done to improve the UX but the idea in itself was worth 5* and the overall experience is worthwhile....also I like the fact that it's a short game and unlike some games u don't have to wait for construction and all..
A great game pretty addicting great progression a good way spend several hours
Purely amazing
This is one of the best text game that I've ever played.
It was vary fun to play i would play more games by this developer.
Absolutely a wonderfully designed game with a LOT of thought put into it. A bit different from the browser version but definitely in a good way
nice
A unique game thats simple yet surprising.

This game is incredible. Start to finish the story and mystery was amazing. The people who created this did a truly amazing job. Thank you for the great game and experience. Many of the complaints people had about this game never bothered me. The game feels complete in its current state and does not feel cumbersome in any way.

More than meets the eye. The store page and even some reviews seem cryptic. This is intentional. Knowing anything about the game ahead of time wont help you, and will only hinder the experience. If you are looking to be surprised by a minimalist experience, play this game. If you dont mind some spoilers then read on: It mixes Idle and roguelike/survival elements as well as real time action and adventure. It's got a second ending which is a great reason to replay it for an additional challenge.
Very entertaining and eerie game. Thanks devs!
a neat little game but the audio tracks don't play when you leave the screen for them like they're supposed to
Brilliant game, so simple and yet so captivating
It was werid at first I didn't know what I was doing but after sticking with it I really enjoyed the game. 😊And I am quite happy that I bought it.
Just a great little game. So engaging, without being demanding.
I highly reccomend this game. It's not your average idle game and is the best text based game I've ever played.

I bought this despite having already played A Dark Night, which is a free version, due to the supposed great story. There's practically no story, just little messages that constantly pop up and annoyingly get in the way. ADN has messages (or a "story") too, but nowhere near as annoying. The games are different enough to play both, and there are things each one does better than the other. I like some things about the layout better in this one, and some things better in ADN. I feel that an official version, especially one that costs money, should be substantially better than a free version, not marginally better, if that. I can't even get myself to play through this one again because of the stupid pop ups every time I collect wood. They need to be moved to the bottom of the screen where they'd be out of the way. I also never figured out the point of the jewels. And supplies should be listed on each page (there's room to do so) or at least have a button to view them on each page, so you don't have to keep going back and forth so much. The concept and game itself are great, but the implementation needs work.

I just don't get all the gushing reviews. A work of art, seriously? The story is hardly there and you will see the same text over and over and over. There are no decisions to be made other than resource management. The start is crushingly slow and boring, although apparently that is a feature not a bug to some people.  It's a clicker game for an endless stream of upgrades followed by a mediocre and very small wilderness roguelike followed by a 30 second arcade sequence. I guess the atmosphere is well done and it's an interesting idea to put the genres together. But mostly what kept me going was wondering if the gameplay was going anywhere to justify all the accolades. It just doesn't and is never challenging. If the fighting keeps you interested for more than a dozen battles with the same thing there is something wrong with you.  And lordy, the commentary is so pompous and self congratulatory. People liked it more than your average clicker game, guys, yet not changing lives or breaking boundaries here...

Some disclaimer: I got this for free during a promotion. I'm playing on a small Sony Xperia phone.  Honeatly this being the "official" version I was hoping it'll have a much nicer interface and be easier to play.  The text log is put at the bottom of the screen, and 90% of the time it's covered by my fingers as I try to reach the buttons. It's awkward to read.   The back button is put at the top left side of the screen, which is awkward to reach with my right thumb (I'm right-handed).   The pop up text is good in that I know some things are happening; I don't read the log much because of its position. But it covers the buttons I'm trying to press. It interrupts my playing flow.  Overall this version of the game is just not very pleasing to play. I'm rather disappointed to be honest, especially since I think most of my grievances can be addressed by switching the text log and the buttons' position.   If you can play the browser version, just play that. It's free, and has a much nicer side-by-side interface.

Are these audio-files accessible online, so I can skip through the parts I've already heard?  A 'Take all' button would've been nice. While I understand limiting healing, having no out-of-combat heal-by-eating felt odd from an in-game character perspective.  While this may seem like a lot of criticism, it's because I really liked playing through this game, and just wished I would've been distracted a bit less so I could've focused more on the wonderful narrative. Anyway, I'm off to try for the 'good' ending. :)

This game's minimalistic design brings the fun of imagining the characters to a game, something that isn't as popular anymore. It's fun to imagine things your own way, rather than being forced to see it in the way the developer does. The darker undertones that develop in the game brought me back time and time again when I first played on iOS. I really liked that the game doesn't coddle and guide you like some other games do. You're left to figure out what you want to do by yourself, just as you would be in real life. I found myself missing this game when I switched to Android devices and was overjoyed when it was finally brought to Android. All in all, thank you Amir and Michael for a fantastic experience.

Excellent Game for a mobile platform. On a technical side, it uses minimal processing power on the battery and does not require any gyroscope or advanced controls, making it playable for a very long time without a charger. Simplicity is it's nature and it executes it so well. The game is fun and addictive for hours at a time. You would never think a game with such simplicity would have so much to explore, capturing attention better than games with far more graphical development and a larger array of features. A must play.

With a beautiful minimalist design and an eerie plot steeped in vague mystery, "A Dark Room" takes you to a strange and dark world. Repetitive motions induce a relaxed state that allows the user to drift through the experience, still anxious with curious ponderings.   A word of caution; power can be dangerous.  UPDATE: After finishing the game I can say with certainty that anyone who enjoys stories, or minimalistic text-based games, or even want a way to idly pass the time, "A Dark Room" is the ideal game for you.   It also holds a powerful message within the gameplay itself. A very entertaining and eye-opening experience.

This is a perfect game. And it's probably the only perfect game I've ever played. As soon as I finished the game, I immediately played through a second time. I've replayed games before, but never immediately after. It's pretty short...it took me about 3 hours each time. This reminds me of a lot of the great games of the 80's. Their graphics were sparse, but they had lots and lots of thought behind every piece. Once you beat the game once, you unlock a cool developer commentary, that I loved. At first, elements of the game seem weird and out of place, but then I realized it all fit together into it's unique story. I found this looking for a text-based adventure game, like Zork. It's a button-pressing game, with no text commands. But it reminded me of what I liked about Zork. Except this game isn't impossible. It's well worth every penny I spent on it, which wasn't much.

A fascinating, intriguing, story-driven throwback to the era of gaming when graphics were literally not possible. The story is a bit like H.P. Lovecraft's Sim City. I can't discuss the gameplay without ruining the story, but the progression of constantly adding new things to figure out (without actually explaining them to the player) works startlingly well.  This is a well designed game and absolutely worth the price. No ads, no IAPs, nothing to distract you. Play for 3 minutes or sit down for 4 hours; it's that adaptable. Great, great game.

I can't say too much about this game without spoiling the experience. If you have $2 to spare buy it. Play it as fast or as slow as you want but buy it.  When I look for indie games, what I want is a compelling narrative and the exploration of ideas and emotions I haven't seen before. A Dark Room delivered.  It might not be your favourite game, but let it be a precious gem of an experience that you find and sink your teeth into all on your own. Let it surprise you and let it draw you in.  If you're interested in game devolopement and story, the game also comes with sound bites where they talk you through their experience making the game. These sound bites alone where worth the small cost.  Thank you to the devolopers for putting in the hard work to make a truly unique and rewarding experience.

i loved adr on browser, and the extra story bits here have me invested again. however, a lot of bugs still exist to detract from enjoyment. first and foremost, any response to any random event crashes the app completely, making it impossible to get the scout perk or respond to the thieves, etc. i've tried uninstalling and reinstalling, but this only deletes my progress, and the issue remains. second, when an item is possible to purchase (such as a trap, hut, etc with sufficient materials), and i press "cancel", the purchase still goes through regardless. finally, though not as gamebreaking, a few other graphical/ui improvements could be made - a "night mode", for instance, such as i always played on browser; perhaps greying out buttons when there are insufficient materials or "can't build any more of these"; and a "story log", containing a record of all plot-related text that has appeared on the top of the screen. overall, i'm very happy with the quality of this story, and hope to see the technical details of the app updated to reflect that quality.
